import pandas as pd 
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.patches as mpatches

INTRODUCTION

We are provided with a dataset offering insights into the AI-driven job market, containing 10 columns as described:

Job_Title: (Categorical) Title of the role.
Industry: (Categorical) Industry the job belongs to.
Company_Size: (Categorical) "Small", "Medium", or "Large".
Location: (Categorical) Geographic location of the role.
AI_Adoption_Level: (Categorical) Extent of AI adoption in the role.
Automation_Risk: (Categorical) Likelihood of job automation in the next 10 years.
Required_Skills: (Categorical) Key skills required for the role.
Salary_USD: (Numeric) Annual salary in USD.
Remote_Friendly: (Categorical) Indicates whether the job can be performed remotely.
Job_Growth_Projection: (Categorical) Projected growth or decline of the role over the next five years.

There are no missing values in the dataset, allowing us to proceed with the analysis. In the following sections, we will explore several insights, such as how AI adoption influences salary and job growth, which industries face the highest automation risks, and the extent to which roles offer remote flexibility. Additionally, we will examine the skills associated with automation risks and investigate whether company size affects AI adoption and job growth projections.

RESULTS

This analysis provides a detailed look at the AI-driven job market, focusing on automation risks, job growth, and salary trends. We identified healthcare as the safest industry, while transportation faces the highest automation risk. Education and finance sectors show promising job growth, while manufacturing is in decline. The finance industry tends to offer higher salaries, particularly for Product Managers, while transportation salaries are generally lower. Finally, roles such as Data Scientist and Operations Manager present low automation risks and strong growth potential, making them desirable career choices.

Task 1: Which industry does AI pose the largest threat to?¶

In [6]:
grouped = df.groupby(['Industry', 'Automation_Risk']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)
grouped_percent = grouped.div(grouped.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100
In [7]:
industries = grouped.index
low_risk = grouped_percent['Low']
medium_risk = grouped_percent['Medium']
high_risk = grouped_percent['High']

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# Stacked bars
plt.bar(industries, low_risk, label='Low', color='blue')
plt.bar(industries, medium_risk, bottom=low_risk, label='Medium', color='orange')
plt.bar(industries, high_risk, bottom=low_risk+medium_risk, label='High', color='green')

# Rotate x-ticks for better readability 
plt.xticks(rotation=90)

# Add a title, y-axis, and legend
plt.title("Industry Separated by Automation Risk")
plt.legend(title='Automation Risk Level')
plt.ylabel("Percent of Jobs ")
# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

From the graph, we can see that automation risk levels are similar across industries. Energy appears to be the safest, with the largest low-risk workers, while transportation has the highest risk, with a large portion of workers in the medium to high-risk category. Only around 17% of jobs across industries are considered low-risk for automation.

The job growth chart shows the education and finance sector will see the most growth, and manufacturing the largest decline. Energy shows a demising 40% decline rate, while transportation also shows steady job growth despite its higher automation risk.

It may be interesting to group the salary information by job to get the spread of pay.

In [11]:
# Filter for Finance industry
finance_jobs = df[df['Industry'] == 'Finance']

# Group by Job_Title and calculate the mean salary
top_finance_jobs = finance_jobs.groupby('Job_Title')['Salary_USD'].mean().reset_index()

# Sort by Salary and select the top 10 highest paying jobs
top_finance_jobs = top_finance_jobs.sort_values(by='Salary_USD', ascending=False)

# Create bar plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x='Salary_USD', y='Job_Title', data=top_finance_jobs)

# Customizing plot
plt.title('Salary ranking for Jobs in the Finance Industry')
plt.xlabel('Average Salary (USD)')
plt.ylabel('Job Title')
plt.show()

In [13]:
df['AI_Adoption_Level'] = pd.Categorical(df['AI_Adoption_Level'], categories=['Low', 'Medium', 'High'], ordered=True)

cross_tab = pd.crosstab(df['Company_Size'], df['AI_Adoption_Level'])
cross_tab_percent = cross_tab.div(cross_tab.sum().sum()).multiply(100)
# Plot the heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.heatmap(cross_tab_percent, annot=True, cmap='Blues', fmt='.2f')
plt.title('Heatmap of Company Size vs AI Adoption Level (Relative Percentages)')
plt.xlabel('AI Adoption Level')
plt.ylabel('Company Size')
plt.show()

This shows that there is a there is a fairly low and even threat of AI Adoption for different sized companies.

In [17]:
industry_salary = df.groupby('Job_Title')['Salary_USD'].agg(['mean', 'std']).reset_index()
industry_salary = industry_salary.sort_values(by='mean', ascending=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x='Job_Title', y='mean', data=industry_salary, yerr=industry_salary['std'])
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('Average Salary by Job Title with Error Bars')
plt.ylabel('Average Salary (USD)')
plt.xlabel('Job Title')
plt.show()

When examining job title without separating by industry we can see the highest paying job, on average, is an Operations Manager, while the lowest paying job is a Software Engineer. These results are interesting given highest paying jobs in the best industries.
